AUDIO: 'a full commercial I made completely with AI on this laptop. And [music] here\'s why you\'ll want to stick around with. By the end of this video, you\'ll be able to make one of these yourself for your product, your brand, or just an idea you\'ve been sitting on for years.'

[01:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; A real cinematic ad. And honestly, it\'s way simpler than it looks. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; And the skill that built the whole thing free in the description. You walk away with everything I use here. It\'s three simple steps. Step one, the assets.'

[01:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Product, characters, [music] locations, props in Soul Cinema and GPT Image 2.0. Step two, the cloth skill that turns the story [music] into prompts. Step three, generating the scenes in Cites 2.0. All'

[01:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'inside Kicks AI. All right, let\'s get right into it. Stage one, creating the assets. Here\'s how we\'ll do this. [music] I\'m going to generate different options for'

[01:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the characters and the locations, test them, and lock the ones [music] that perform best. You will see why this matters later. But before we generate anything, we have to get organized. You\'re about to [music] make a ton of files, and if they\'re scattered'

[01:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'everywhere, you\'ll waste half your day digging through the images mid-edit. I\'ve got one image of the headphones, and [music] one isn\'t enough. The model needs to see them from every angle, or it\'ll hallucinate halfway through a'

[02:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scene. So, I\'m going to drop my image into GPT Image 2.0. This is the best model right now for product [music] editing, and I\'m going to ask for a clean product sheet. So, I\'m just saying, "Make a product sheet'

[02:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with front [music] and 3/4 views of the headphones from image one." And [music] I\'m attaching the image. All right, we\'ve got our product sheet. Now, Soul Cinema knows [music] the product from all different sides.'

[02:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'My story has one main character, one guy, and he\'s in every single scene: the kitchen, the stadium, the street, [music] even the office. Headphones on the whole time, always locked into the music. So, to bring this whole thing to'

[02:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'life, I need to build [music] his character sheet, plus all the locations, and all the props. Let\'s start with him. So, for the hero, I\'m using Soul Cinema. This is the best model for'

[02:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'photorealistic looks. I\'m going to go over to Claude and ask for a character sheet. I\'m going to say, "Create a prompt for a character sheet of a young man with an expressive face,'

[03:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'two panels, &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; close-up and full body, front and back on a gray background." I\'m using Claude because it writes the whole detailed prompt for me. And here\'s the [music] point: the close-up gives the model the exact face to look onto,'

[03:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and the full body gives its height [music] and the built. One clean reference for exactly who the guy is, right from the start. Also, the gray background is very important. We found that [music] the win rate is just way'

[03:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'higher on gray because there\'s zero background clutter competing with the character. More of what you generate comes back [music] usable. Eight images cost only one credit in Soul Cinema, so I go wild, run a bunch of batches, and'

[03:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scroll until the face stops me. And [music] here\'s a very important tip. Don\'t pick just one. Grab a couple you like and test them. Why? Because the face that looks great as a still'

[04:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; might fall apart the moment it moves and I won\'t know which one holds up until I test them. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; So, I\'m going to keep these two and decide later with actual footage. For now, I drag both onto my canvas. Quick note on the canvas, since I\'m'

[04:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'using it the whole time, it\'s basically just my work space. I lay every candidate side by side, compare them, and drag the winner to the top to lock it. Everything is right there in the view, so nothing gets [music] lost. Let\'s move on to the next asset. The'

[04:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hero is the one that has to carry the [music] whole thing, so he gets the care. The boss is a side character, he doesn\'t need that. So, I\'m not going to overthink him. I\'m using AI cast here because it delivers [music] instant'

[04:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'character sheets and multiple styling options from a single prompt. You can build an entire cast with this, but [music] let\'s start simple. I\'ll type an office boss in his 50s [music] with a pot belly wearing a suit.'

[04:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'All right, some of these are too friendly. I want a boss who\'s genuinely furious. Like this guy over here. I mean, look at that. Pure villain, he\'s perfect for our'

[05:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'story. All right, the boss is done. Let\'s move on. Now, this is the part that makes or breaks the whole video. If your location looks fake or plasticky, no prompting will ever save it. I want one thing'

[05:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'across all of them, bright, clean, high-budget commercial vibe. Same approach, cinematic locations, simple prompt, lots of batches. First, [music] the kitchen. So, I\'m looking for a modern apartment'

[05:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kitchen. Again, three-quarter angle, bright, [music] clean daylight, high-end commercial look. And hit generate. One quick trick, [music] I generate the kitchen at a three-quarter angle. It gives the room more depth for us viewers'

[05:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to hold on to when the camera [music] moves, which gives a way better win rate than a flat head-on shot. Same as the hero, I\'m keeping multiple options here for the kitchen. [music] The first one\'s got that perfect warm'

[05:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'atmosphere. The second one\'s brighter, crisper. Now I\'ve got everything for the first real test. Two heroes, two kitchens. So, I\'m going to use a simple prompt. The hero walks into the'

[06:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kitchen, headphones on, dance a little. Plus the location, the character sheet, and headphones attached. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; This is the part most people skip. Same prompt every single time, and I only swap the hero or the [music] kitchen,'

[06:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'nothing else. Change one thing at a time, and you could actually see what\'s making the [music] difference. All right, let\'s see what we got. Side by side, it\'s obvious. So, the first location [music] in both, the faces just vanish. It\'s too'

[06:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dark, and [music] the whole shot sinks into shadow. The second one\'s brighter, more polished. [music] Looks like an actual commercial. That\'s the winner for the location. And for the character,'

[06:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the curly-haired guy [music] owns the frame. He\'s a better dancer, has better presence, and he just fits in the space. So, that\'s it. We\'re going to go [music] with character A and kitchen B. On our canvas, the winners to the top'

[07:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and locked. And immediately a problem. When animating, I need the hero to make coffee [music] and then leave. So, we need a couple tweaks for the location before we can move forward. I\'m going to'

[07:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bring that kitchen over to GPT [music] image 2.0 and say, "Uh clear everything off the kitchen island so the top is empty. On the left counter, [music] add gas stove.'

[07:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'On the right wall, remove the TV and put a door there instead. Keep everything else the same." And we generate. [music] All right, there we go. Now, first'

[07:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'location is locked. And one more very important thing before we make the next location. After enough generations, you start spotting the same problem before it bites [music] you. And here\'s one pro tip learned the hard way.'

[07:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Look at this character sheet. Multiple faces in one image. Looks fine now, but when we animate later, the video model [music] doesn\'t know which face to grab, so it drifts. There\'s an easy and a very effective solution.'

[08:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'m going to bring my character sheet over to GPT MS 2.0 and say, "Erase the [music] face from the full body shot on the right panel." And just like that, one face [music] to lock onto, and he\'s all set. And I\'m'

[08:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to quickly do the same for the boss as well. Attach the image and do it again. Now, both faces are locked. All right, let\'s keep building. Now, the other locations, &gt;&gt; [music]'

[08:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; same way. Generate, keep the best, onto the canvas. The stadium, I\'ll be honest, I didn\'t want to handwrite a prompt for [music] a cinematic stadium from scratch, so I didn\'t. I\'m giving Claude three things. Running track,'

[08:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'three-quarter view, sunny day. And notice the three-quarter view, same trick as the kitchen. I generate the location at an angle to have a better hit rate. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; Now, let it cook, and it came back with a full detailed prompt with a track, the'

[08:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'field, [music] and the light description. And the result is exactly what I wanted. Perfect green field, [music] red track, clean light. I\'m also going to bring two options [music] that I like'

[09:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to the canvas. And just like the kitchen, I don\'t trust the still, I test them. Same character sheet, [music] both stadiums, one simple line. He runs along the track in headphones. All right, this one\'s clear. I\'m going'

[09:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to go with the first one. The line\'s just way better for what I need. It\'s brighter, [music] and this is a morning scene, so it has to feel like morning. Again, winner to the [music] top, locked.'

[09:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then, the street corner and the office, same [music] process for each. Generate a couple options, keep my favorites on the canvas, test them, see what works best, and finally lock them. &gt;&gt; [music]'

[09:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Here, testing every single location might feel slow, but it\'s not. This is exactly how you avoid wasting a ton of credits later trying to generate [music] full scenes with the wrong assets. Last thing, through every one of these tests, my hero\'s been in a plain black'

[10:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'outfit, &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; and that\'s fine for tests, but now that everything is locked, let\'s give him a real look, and here\'s how. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; I\'m going to open up Claude, drop in an image of our character, and say,'

[10:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '"Give me 10 casual outfit ideas for this character. Write each as a prompt." Now, it\'s giving me super detailed [music] prompts for each outfit. I run all 10 in Jupiter M 2.0 and'

[10:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'compare. Okay. So many decent looks. Honestly, I\'d probably wear half of these myself. Here, I love the top in one'

[10:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and the jeans in another. So, I\'m not going to settle. I\'ll [music] ask, "Take the shirt from the second look, make it pink, and keep the jeans from the first. Combine them into one'

[10:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prompt." And run that again. All right, so we have a pink shirt, white tee, the jeans. Now, here\'s the guy. And one last pro tip, and trust me,'

[11:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] this one is a lifesaver for your credits. Every time you edit an asset, the quality takes a hit. We built this character in Soul Cinema, and the quality came out crisp, right down to the skin texture. But, when we ran it through Jupiter Image for the edits, it'

[11:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'softened everything up, and that\'s exactly how you get that flat, plastic, AI slop look, which we definitely don\'t want. Goal is keeping it looking real. [music] So, here\'s the play. You take your'

[11:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'original, high-detailed Soul Cinema shot [music] and your newly edited GPT image version and you pull them both into a photo editor any basic editor works just fine. Soul shot on top, edited version underneath.'

[11:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Mask out the old outfit on top, the new one &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; shows through from below. Face, the skin, the background, all from the original stays Soul. Only the outfit comes from the edit. And lastly, the'

[11:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'props. The Sky Dancer, the sneakers, the backpack, they repeat across scenes, so each gets a clean reference sheet into GPT image 2.0. No motion tests on these, they\'re objects, they don\'t perform. The'

[12:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prop sheet\'s enough. That\'s everything built, tested, [music] and locked. Now, we\'ll turn it into videos. Stage two, the shot list. Stage one gave me a pile of locked'

[12:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'assets. Stage [music] two turns them into actual prompts. And this is where most people bleed credits. Here\'s the trap. You open SeaDance, you start typing a prompt from scratch, you overload it, you hate the result, tweak'

[12:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it, run it again [music] and 20 generations later, you\'ve spent a fortune and your initial idea is a mess. Let me show you how to fix that. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; First, I never write prompts by hand. I use a skill I built in Claude.'

[12:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Quickly on what that does, since [music] it\'s the engine of the whole stage. A skill is a file you load into Claude that teaches [music] it to do one job exactly your way. This one does a single thing. It writes'

[12:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shot lists with prompts tailored for SeaDance 2.0. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; Everything we learned making our last film, how SeaDance wants a shot described, what holds character consistency, what breaks it, all of it is packed'

[13:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; into this one file. It\'s in the description, load it once and Claude stops guessing [music] and starts writing prompts like we would. New chat, now I give it three things. [music] First, the script. I wrote the whole ad out beforehand [music]'

[13:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and the idea behind it is super simple. You know that feeling when everything is loud at once, the mower outside, the traffic, [music] your boss. This is the ad. A guy\'s morning and one tap on his headphones switches the whole world off.'

[13:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; One beat per scene. Second, every locked asset. This is the part most people skip and it\'s why their prompts come out generic. I don\'t [music] just describe the assets to Claude, I upload them. All of them straight from the canvas.'

[13:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] The more it can actually see, the better it writes. And third, I name each one so Claude knows [music] exactly what it\'s looking at. Now, it cooks. Every scene broken into prompts, each one [music] written'

[14:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for C dance. And here\'s the thing I want you to understand before we touch it because [music] it changes how you work. This isn\'t a pile of separate prompts, it\'s a shot [music] list. One connected document. It\'s connected two ways that'

[14:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'matter. This block at the top is [music] the style prefix, lighting, camera, color, the whole look. It\'s glued to every single prompt in the document. You change it [music] once and it changes'

[14:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'everywhere. You watch me do exactly that in a minute and every prompt has a name [music] so I can talk to Claude like an editor and say, "Edit prompt 1A, do this." And only that one changes. Everything else stays locked. [music]'

[14:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That\'s the whole advantage over prompting one at a time. You\'re not juggling 20 loose [music] chats. You\'re editing one connected thing. That\'s the framework. Now, let\'s generate and watch it break [music] and watch me fix it.'

[14:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Stage three, scene generation. Now, I\'m not going to say that the first try works because it rarely does. So, I\'m going to [music] run each prompt, tell you exactly what\'s wrong, and show you what I\'m typing back to Claude'

[15:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] to fix it. So, I\'m grabbing the first prompt. Now, before I generate it, guess what I\'m [music] going to do. In my project, I\'m saving all the assets that I\'ve locked, the characters, locations, props &gt;&gt; [music]'

[15:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; as elements. And I\'m going to name each one the same way I did in Claude. And now watch this. I\'m going to paste in the first prompt [music] to the shot list gave me, and all the required images get attached automatically. So, I don\'t have to do'

[15:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'anything separately. [music] All right, let\'s run it in C dance and see what we get. Hmm, I see what\'s wrong here. So, first the light. This commercial needs bright, [music] clean morning energy. Second,'

[15:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the camera. It\'s just sitting there static. [music] I want it moving from frame one. Three, the coffee is crammed into the end of the same shot. It\'s just doing too much. I want to'

[15:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tease the coffee here and give it its own prompt after. So, here\'s how we fix it. In Claude, I\'m going [music] to say change the style prefix for the whole shot list. Kill the contra jour and shadow side framing.'

[16:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Uh, let\'s go soft even daylight from the camera side, bright and clean. And I\'m going to say apply to every prompt. This will fix the lighting in all scenes right away.'

[16:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now the one A prompt specific stuff. Edit prompt one A. Uh, I want the shot open [music] behind him and ease around to profile as he walks to the stove.'

[16:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'No static wide and cut the coffee down to a quick three stage jump cut tease. Set the moka, gargles, he pours and sips. [music]'

[16:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now Claude is giving me the updated shot list. The light is fixed in every scene and one A is rewritten. I\'m going to copy the new one A and paste it into C dance. Let\'s see what we get. Okay, better. The camera is moving now and &gt;&gt; [music]'

[17:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; that bright clean light is exactly the morning feel I wanted. From all the one A runs, I grabbed the slices that work. The walk in from one, the headphones on beat from another. But the coffee making, it just looks bad. It\'s rushed, [music] flat, there\'s no weight to it.'

[17:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, let\'s pull that moment out on its own, its own shot, its own prompt. I\'m going to call it 1B. We build it from scratch. I want a fast, [music] snappy edit of the coffee making process. But first, props. The moka and the mug came'

[17:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'out different in every take, drifting cut to cut. And in a tight close-up, that\'s the first thing your eye sees. So, I\'m going to lock them. One clean reference each. In Claude, I\'m asking'

[17:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'create the prompts for a moka pot and a mug that match the kitchen. Couple seconds and here\'s what it gives me. The mug and the moka prompts. I\'m going to paste those into GPT image two,'

[17:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'roll a bunch of options, and grab the cream colored ones. They match the product. Now, I\'m going to add them to my elements. Let\'s name them moka cream and mug'

[18:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cream. Now, they\'ll auto attach same as everything else. And let\'s go back to Claude and ask for the new prompt. Add an intermediate prompt 1B.'

[18:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Turn the coffee into &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; a fast cut montage, high angle close-up, straight down on the moka. Uh I want a worm\'s eye from [music] the burner looking up as the flame'

[18:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'catches. Uh tight on the pour, the sip, cut fast, make him feel [music] the music. And I\'m also going to attach my elements and say lock moka cream and'

[18:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mug cream [music] as exact references. Okay, now that\'s a commercial. Coffee shot like a car ad. I rolled it a bunch and pulled [music] keeper faces off four different videos. The spoon from one,'

[18:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the flame from another, [music] the pour from a third, the sip from a fourth. Okay, now the last beat, the exit. This is the old 1B from the original shot list. So, now [music] it slides is to 1C. Let me run the original prompt'

[19:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'first. Hmm. I don\'t like his moves. Him just walking out like that, too boring. I want him enjoying the music. [music] You know that feeling when you leave the house still dancing a little?'

[19:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That kind of move. And here\'s a pro tip, this is a big one. You don\'t just write dances or type a generic [music] description of motion. That means nothing to SeeDance. You have to spell it out move by move. So, I\'m'

[19:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'asking Claude to add a more detailed choreography without changing the story. Rewrite prompt 1C, the exit. He packs his sneakers into the bag, zips it, [music]'

[19:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then dances to the door. Add dance moves. Um &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; I\'m going to be very specific here. So, I want two head nods, shoulder rolling one at a time, a knee dip, a finger snap, a quarter spin at the [music]'

[20:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'door, um also going to say keep it loose, keep it fun, and on a tap of the ear cup. And run it. Now, here we also do the edit, so'

[20:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pulling faces from three different takes. The zip from one, the dance from another, the tap from a third. And that tap at the end, [music] we\'re going to use the same motion, basically cutting on action most of the time. Now, let\'s'

[20:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'watch [music] what scene one looks like edited. &gt;&gt; [snorts] [music]'

[20:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Three prompts, nine generations, keeper faces of nine different 15-second clips. That\'s scene one. Now, the stadium.'

[20:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Let\'s start with prompt 2A. Okay, the stadium, completely different energy. And the first thing I deal with isn\'t a prompt, it\'s his clothes. My hero\'s lock sheet is [music] in his casual'

[21:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'look, the pink shirt. He\'s not running around in a button-down. So, before I generate a single frame, [music] I build him an athletic version. I\'m going to go over to Claude, attach his khaki sheet,'

[21:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and [music] also drop the sneakers as a reference. I\'m going to say, "Give me a prompt to edit this character sheet so that he\'s wearing a blue athletic outfit with these sneakers." A quick thing before people get this'

[21:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'wrong, since I need to stitch slices from different [music] takes together, the outfit would jump. Every generation would give him different shorts [music] or different shoes. To stop that, I lock the outfit down as a reference. I take'

[21:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Claude\'s prompt into GPT Image 2, feed it the character sheet plus the sneakers, [music] and generate a few solid consistent options. Let\'s see what we got. All right, I\'m going to choose this blue'

[21:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'outfit. That\'s my dry athletic [music] hero into elements as S Hero. Now, here\'s the move that saves me 10 minutes [music] from now. I\'ll create a'

[22:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'second sheet, same guy, same outfit, soaked, because he\'s about to sprint, [music] and by the finish, he needs to be drenched. And if I take a dry reference and ask Heathens to sweat him up with words, he starts improvising, and the'

[22:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'face drips off of him. So, I\'m going to make the wet version now on purpose. I\'ll attach the character sheet and ask, "Same character sheet, post-run, sweaty chest, sweat stains on the'

[22:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shirt." Let\'s save it as S Hero Wet. Two sheets, one dry, one wet. That\'s the rule. If your character has to [music] change mid-sentence,'

[22:44] [scene:talk]
